commodity narrative:
Demand for cheese is steady in food service markets, though some stakeholders say retail demand is softening and below some previously forecasted levels. Export demand is strong as domestically produced loads are being sold at a discount to loads produced in international markets. Some export sellers say purchasers in Asia are looking to secure loads for Q2 2023 delivery. Market prices for barrels and blocks saw steep declines on the CME throughout last week, with prices for both falling below $2. Through the start of this week, prices have recovered somewhat but both remain down compared to this time last week. Some stakeholders attribute these lower prices to increased spot availability for both cheese barrels and blocks in recent weeks. Milk is available for cheesemakers to run steady production schedules. Some plant managers say labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies continue to limit their ability to run full schedules.

In the West, wholesale prices are down $.1825 for process, and down $0.0500 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

commodity narrative:
In the West, retail demand for cheese is declining and remains below some stakeholders' expectations. This decline is, reportedly, due to higher grocery prices which are causing some retail customers to change their cheese purchasing habits. Meanwhile, stakeholders say food service demand for cheese is unchanged this week. Strong export demand is present, as contacts report continued interest from Asian purchasers who are securing loads for delivery into Q2 of next year. Cheese production is steady, though some plant managers say labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies are preventing them from running full schedules. On October 25th cheese block loads traded at prices higher than barrels on the CME for the first time since early August. Contacts report recent increases in barrel production and spot availability have contributed to a $0.2250 decline in prices since last Wednesday. In that same time frame cheese block prices have decreased by $0.0525. Spot loads of cheese blocks are also available for purchasing.

In the West, wholesale prices are down $.0200 for process, but up $0.0075 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

commodity narrative:
Cheese sales are steady to food service markets, in the West, though contacts note lighter demand from retail purchasers. Inflationary pressures are affecting some retail customers who are, reportedly, buying smaller cheese packages or switching to private label brands. Export demand for cheese remains strong as some purchasers say they are receiving plenty of interest from purchasers in Asian markets who are looking to secure loads for delivery in 2023. Cheese blocks are available for purchasing on the spot market, but cheese barrel inventories remain tighter. Cooler weather in the region is contributing to increased cow comfort and milk output. Cheesemakers say they are utilizing available milk supplies to run busy production schedules. Some plant managers say they are running below capacity due to labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies. 

In the West, wholesale prices are down $.0450 for process, but up $0.0300 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

commodity narrative:
In the West, demand for cheese is steady from food service purchasers. Meanwhile, retail demand is softening as higher prices have caused some purchasers to switch to smaller cheese packages or to private label brands. Strong demand is present from export purchasers, who continue to source loads of cheese from the US at a discount to loads produced in some other countries. Export data released by the USDA Foreign Agricultural Service on October 5, 2022, showed that exports of cheese in August were up 5% from 2021, and year to date exports were up 13% compared to last year. Spot purchasers say loads of cheese blocks are available for purchasing. Cheese barrel inventories are tighter and more difficult for purchasers to obtain. Milk output is improving in the region; cheesemakers say milk volumes are available for steady production. Labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies continue to prevent some plant managers from running full schedules.

In the West, wholesale prices are up $.0300 for process, and up $0.0275 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are down $0.2000 from the previous week.

commodity narrative:
Retail demand for cheese is declining in the West, as higher grocery store prices are causing some customers to change their purchasing habits. Demand for cheese is steady from food service customers, though mozzarella makers continue to note strong purchasing from pizza makers. Internationally produced loads of cheese are being sold at a premium to loads produced in the US, this is contributing to increased interest from export purchasers. Since last Wednesday, the price for cheese barrels has increased by 11.5 cents on the CME. Cheese block prices have declined by 2.75 cents in that time frame. Spot purchasers say demand for barrels are outpacing supplies, contributing to tighter spot availability. Meanwhile, spot inventories of cheese blocks are available for purchasing. Milk volumes are tightening, but cheesemakers say supplies are sufficient to run steady production schedules. Plant managers in the region say labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies are preventing them from running at or near capacity.

In the West, wholesale prices are up $0.1325 for process, and up $0.1825 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

Demand for cheese is strengthening in both retail and food service markets. Stakeholders say they are selling more loads of mozzarella cheese to pizzamakers. commodity narrative:
Retail demand for cheese is unchanged in domestic markets. Meanwhile, food service demand is trending higher. Contacts note increased mozzarella cheese sales to regional pizzamakers. Domestically produced loads are competitively price for international markets, and contacts say this is contributing to strong export demand. Spot purchasers say that cheese barrel and block inventories are available, but tightening. Market prices for barrels have climbed 8.5 cents, on the CME, since last Wednesday. Cheese makers are running near capacity, though some plant managers report lighter production schedules due to labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies.

EXPORT ASSISTANCE
This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance on contracts to sell 3.2 million pounds (1,472 metric tons) of American-type cheese. So far this year, the program has assisted member cooperatives who have contracts to sell 70.1 million pounds of American-type cheeses and 7.1 million pounds of cream cheese in export markets.

When combined with butter, AMF, cream cheese and whole milk powder, the program has assisted members with sales of 930 million pounds of milk on a milkfat basis.

commodity narrative:
Milk is available for cheese makers to run busy production schedules in the West. Labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies are contributing to some reduced regional production schedules. Export demand for cheese is steady to higher, as contacts say current market prices are favorable to international purchasers. Domestic demand has seen a small uptick this week as spot purchasers have been more willing to pick up loads at current market prices. Despite this uptick, stakeholders say retail and food service sales of cheese are below some previously forecasted levels. Some grocery customers in the region say higher prices are causing grocery store shoppers to reduce their cheese use. In food service markets, restauranteurs are reducing their operating hours and their menu offerings due to labor shortages, higher input costs, and reduced customer traffic. Inventories of cheese barrels and blocks are available for spot purchasing. 

In the West, wholesale prices are up $.0550 for process, but down $0.0050 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

commodity narrative:
Retail demand for cheese is steady to lower; contacts report higher retail prices are causing some customers to change their purchasing habits. Food service demand for cheese is also softening in the region. Meanwhile, contacts report strong export demand for cheese as domestically produced loads of cheese are priced competitively to orders coming from other countries. Some Asian purchasers are, reportedly, ordering loads of cheese to ship in early Q2 of 2023. Spot inventories of both cheese barrels and blocks are available throughout the region. Regional milk inventories are available for cheese makers to run busy schedules. Cheese production is steady to lower this week, as some production facilities had planned down time for the holiday weekend. Some plant managers say labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies continue to have a negative impact on their ability to run full schedules. 

In the West, wholesale prices are up $.0150 for process, and up $0.0625 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are up $0.2250 from the previous week.
secondary source info:
The CME Group June monthly average price for barrels was $2.2077, compared to $2.3567 in May. The June average price for blocks was $2.1902, compared to $2.3293 in May. 


EXPORT ASSISTANCE
This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance on contracts to sell 500,000 pounds (226 metric tons) of American-type cheese and 560,000 (272 metric tons) of cream cheese. So far this year, the program has assisted member cooperatives who have contracts to sell 53.5 million pounds of American-type cheeses and 5.6 million pounds of cream cheese in export markets.

When combined with butter, AMF, cream cheese and whole milk powder, the program has assisted members with sales of 754 million pounds of milk on a milkfat basis.
methodology: Information for the period July 4 - 8, 2022, issued weekly

methodology: Information for the period June 20 - 24, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
Demand for cheese is trending lower across both retail and food service markets, in the West. Stakeholders say that some restaurants in the region are reducing operating hours due to high food costs, reduced consumer spending, and labor shortages. Meanwhile, export demand for cheese is strong and contacts continue to report steady interest from purchasers in Asian markets. Market prices for both cheese barrels and blocks have slid lower, on the CME, since last Wednesday. Some stakeholders say that prices are being affected by softening domestic demand and an increase in spot availability. Cheesemakers are running busy schedules, as Class III milk remains available for production in the region. Some plant managers report that they are running below capacity due to labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies. 

In the West, wholesale prices are down $.0800 for process, and down $0.1025 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

commodity narrative:
Cheese sales are trending lower in the retail sector. Food service orders are also faltering. Amid high input costs, ongoing labor pool issues, and consumer resistance to upward price pressures, some eateries are offering streamlined menu options and/or serving during abbreviated hours of operation. Export cheese demand, on the other hand, remains robust. Inquiries are steady from international customers. Some contacts report buyers in Asia are already looking to lock down cheese orders into Q1 of 2023. Western cheese production is busy. Milk is available for cheesemaking. Market participants report that Class III milk intakes are at maximum capacity for some plants. Other plants are running under capacity due to production/packaging supply delays and staffing shortages. Regional cheese inventories are generally stable to growing. Contacts say both barrel and block spot supplies are available at this time. 

In the West, wholesale prices are down $.0200 for process, but up $0.0200 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

Retail demand is also trending lower; some contacts say that increased costs are pushing some customers to reduce their cheese purchasing. In contrast, export demand for cheese is strong with contacts reporting steady purchasing from international customers, with some in Asia looking for loads to ship in Q1 of 2023. Some plant managers say that continued labor shortages and delays to production supplies are preventing them from running at capacity.

commodity narrative:
International demand for cheese is strong in the West, as contacts report continued purchasing of loads for export to Asia in Q1 of 2023. In domestic markets, demand for cheese is steady from both retail and food service customers. Stakeholders say that port congestion and a shortage of available truck drivers are causing delays in deliveries of cheese loads. Spot inventories of both blocks and barrels are available. Since last Wednesday, market prices for cheese barrels have been mostly steady on the CME, while block prices have fallen. Stakeholders say that large inventories of blocks in cold storage may be contributing some bearishness to cheese markets. Cheese makers are running busy schedules as milk supplies are ample in the region though some plant managers say that they are running below capacity. These contacts relay that labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies are preventing them from running full schedules.

WESTERN WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
In the West, wholesale prices are down $.1025 for process, and down $.0575 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

Stakeholders say that large inventories of blocks in cold storage may be contributing some bearishness to cheese markets. Cheese makers are running busy schedules as milk supplies are ample in the region though some plant managers say that they are running below capacity. These contacts relay that labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies are preventing them from running full schedules.

Export demand for cheese is strong; contacts report that purchasers in Asian countries continue to purchase loads for shipment in Q4 of 2022. commodity narrative:
Cheesemakers say that demand for cheese is strong from both domestic and international purchasers. On the domestic side, retail sales of cheese are steady, while food service purchasing is increasing. Restaurateurs say that warmer weather and lightening COVID restrictions are contributing to increased patronage. International demand for cheese is strong, and contacts report that some Asian purchasers have increased their purchasing for loads of cheese to ship for the end of 2022 and into 2023. Stakeholders continue to cite port congestion as a hindrance to moving increased volumes of cheese to export markets. Cheese producers are running busy schedules in the region, as they work through available supplies of milk. Some plant managers relay that they are limited from running at capacity by labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies. Spot purchasers report that cheese inventories are available, in the West.

In the West, wholesale prices are up $.0875 for process, and up $.0425 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

commodity narrative:
Demand for cheese is steady, in the West, across both retail and food service markets. Meanwhile, international demand for cheese is strong. Market prices for cheese moved higher on the CME, since last Wednesday. Despite increasing prices, contacts report that cheese produced domestically is being sold at favorable prices compared to internationally produced loads. Stakeholders say that this price discrepancy is contributing to strong export demand, and that Asian purchasers continue to show interest in buying loads to ship in early 2023. Port congestion and a shortage of available truck drivers are causing delays to both export and domestic loads of cheese. Cheese inventories are available for spot purchasing in the region. Milk production is steady to higher throughout the region, leaving supplies available for cheesemakers to run busy schedules. Cheese production is active, though some plant managers say that labor shortages are preventing them from running at capacity.

In the West, wholesale prices are up $.0900 for process, and up $.0625 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

Port congestion and a shortage of available truck drivers are causing delays to both export and domestic loads of cheese. Cheese inventories are available for spot purchasing in the region. Milk production is steady to higher throughout the region, leaving supplies available for cheesemakers to run busy schedules. Cheese production is active, though some plant managers say that labor shortages are preventing them from running at capacity. 

WESTERN WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
In the West, wholesale prices are up $.0900 for process, and up $.0625 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

methodology: Information for the period April 4 - 8, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
Cheese makers say that export demand remains strong, as purchasers look to the U.S. for loads that are sold at a discount to internationally produced loads. Some purchasers in Asia are, reportedly, interested in buying loads to ship in late Q4 of 2022 and early Q1 of 2023. Domestic demand for cheese is steady in retail markets, while food service demand is increasing. Contacts report that loosening COVID restrictions and warmer weather have contributed to increased restaurant traffic. Spot availability for cheese is trending higher in the region. Port congestion and a shortage of truck drivers continue to cause delays to the delivery of loads and production supplies. Cheese producers are running busy schedules to work through available supplies of milk, though some plant managers say that labor shortages and delayed production supply deliveries are preventing them from running at capacity. 

WESTERN WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
In the West, wholesale prices are down $.1650 for process, and up $.1075 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.
secondary source info:
EXPORT ASSISTANCE
This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance on contracts to sell 406,000 pounds (184 metric tons) of American-type cheese. So far this year, the program has assisted member cooperatives who have contracts to sell 36.4 million pounds of American-type cheeses and 3.4 million pounds of cream cheese in export markets.

When combined with butter, AMF, cream cheese and whole milk powder, the program has assisted members with sales of 471 million pounds of milk on a milkfat basis.

commodity narrative:
In the West, export demand for cheese is strong as contacts report that international purchasers are looking for loads to meet projected fourth quarter needs. Stakeholders say that there is notable demand from Asian purchasers as cheese produced in the U.S. is priced at a discount to loads made in other countries. Domestic demand for cheese is steady to higher. Contacts report that warmer weather and loosening COVID restrictions are contributing to higher food service cheese purchasing. Cheese inventories are available, though spot purchasers say that inventories have tightened in recent weeks. Contacts report that load deliveries continue to face delays due to port congestion and a shortage of available truck drivers. Western cheesemakers are running busy schedules to work through available milk supplies. Some plant managers report that labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies are causing them to run below capacity.

In the West, wholesale prices are down $.0425 for process, and down $.0950 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

commodity narrative:
Food service customers have been more active recently as warmer weather and loosening COVID restrictions are having a positive impact on cheese demand, in the West. Contacts report that retail demand is steady. Export demand for cheese is strengthening, driven largely by lower prices offered for U.S. produced loads of cheese in comparison to other internationally produced loads. Contacts say that some purchasers in Asia are looking to secure loads now for their fourth quarter needs. Spot cheese loads are available but, reportedly, tightening. Stakeholders say that port congestion and truck driver shortages continue to delay load deliveries. Cheese makers are pulling heavily on milk supplies in the region, as they are running busy schedules to work through these milk supplies. Plant managers say that labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies are preventing them from running at capacity.

In the West, wholesale prices are up $.1075 for process, and up $.1425 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

Cheese made in the U.S. continues to be priced at a discount compared to loads sold from other countries. Due to this, contacts report an increase in interest from purchasers in international markets. A shortage of truck drivers and port congestion are causing delays to load deliveries. Spot inventories of cheese are steady. Loads of milk and production supplies are facing delays due to a lack of available truck drivers. Some plant managers are reporting that delayed deliveries, combined with labor shortages, are preventing them from running at capacity. Overall cheese production is unchanged, in the West, this week.

The USDA Cold Storage report for January 2022 showed a record high for total natural cheese stocks, but the stocks were only slightly higher than a month ago and were up 3 percent year over year. Cheese production is steady. Some plant managers say that labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies are causing them to run below capacity. 


WESTERN WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
In the West, wholesale prices are up $.0525 for process, and up $.0700 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

EXPORT ASSISTANCE
This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance on contracts to sell 3.6 million pounds (1,655 metric tons) of American-type cheese. So far this year, the program has assisted member cooperatives who have contracts to sell 18.7 million pounds of American-type cheeses and 1.7 million pounds of cream cheese in export markets.

When combined with butter, AMF, cream cheese and whole milk powder, the program has assisted members with sales of 279.6 million pounds of milk on a milkfat basis.
methodology: Information for the period February 7 - 11, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
Retail demand for cheese is steady, in the West, though contacts report that food service demand continues to decline. Contacts note that many restaurants in the region are operating reduced hours or are closed due to COVID concerns and labor shortages. International demand for cheese is strengthening, as contacts report increased interest from purchasers in Mexico and Asian markets. Stakeholders say that U.S. cheese prices are currently lower than European prices. Loads of cheese are facing delays due to a shortage of available truck drivers, while export loads are facing additional delays due to port congestion. Spot inventories of both cheese blocks and barrels are available to meet current market demands. Milk is available for cheese producers to run busy schedules. Some plant managers say that labor shortages and delayed deliveries of production supplies are causing them to reduce production schedules.


WESTERN WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
In the West, wholesale prices are up $.1200 for process, and up $.1075 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are up $.0225 from the previous week.

The January average price for blocks, $1.9065, is up from the December 2021 monthly average of $1.8930, and up from the monthly average of a year ago, $1.7470.

EXPORT ASSISTANCE
This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance on contracts to sell 3.6 million pounds (1,655 metric tons) of American-type cheese. So far this year, the program has assisted member cooperatives who have contracts to sell 18.7 million pounds of American-type cheeses and 1.7 million pounds of cream cheese in export markets.

When combined with butter, AMF, cream cheese and whole milk powder, the program has assisted members with sales of 279.6 million pounds of milk on a milkfat basis.
methodology: Information for the period February 7 - 11, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
In the West, steady demand for cheese is present in retail markets, while food service demand has declined. Some contacts report that many restaurants in the region continue to remain closed due to COVID concerns and labor shortages. International demand is strong, with contacts reporting notable demand for loads to export to both Mexico and Asian markets. Export loads of cheese continue to face delays due to port congestion; some stakeholders have suggested that they are looking for alternative transportation methods to reduce these delays. Further delays to loads are occurring due to a shortage of truck drivers in the region. Cheese block and barrel inventories are available to meet current market demands. Cheese production is steady, though some plant managers say that they are running below capacity due to labor shortages.

WESTERN WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
In the West, wholesale prices are down $.1600 for process, and down $.0825 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.

methodology: Information for the period January 24 - 28, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
Demand for cheese in retail markets is holding steady, while food service demand has slid lower this week. Contacts report that rising COVID cases, in parts of the West, are contributing to declines in food service sales. International demand for cheese is steady, with contacts reporting notable interest for export to Asian markets. When combined with butter, AMF, cream cheese and whole milk powder, the program has assisted members with sales of 31.1 million pounds of milk on a milkfat basis.

commodity narrative:
Demand for cheese is steady at both retail and food service markets, in the West. International demand for cheese is strong, with contacts reporting notable purchasing of loads for export to Asian markets. Stakeholders say that these loads continue to face delays due to port congestion. Domestic loads of cheese are also facing delays due to the ongoing shortage of truck drivers and poor weather in parts of the region. Cheese barrels and blocks are, reportedly, available for spot purchasing. Cheese markets are mixed. Since last Wednesday, CME prices for blocks have fallen by 1.25 cents, while barrel prices increased by 3.25 cents. Milk is available in the region, though some producers report that extreme weather is preventing supplies from reaching cheese plants. Cheese production is steady to lower, some plant managers report that delays to production supplies and labor shortages are causing them to run reduced schedules. 

WESTERN WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
In the West, wholesale prices are up $.1400 for process, and up $.0700 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are up $.1450 from the previous week.

commodity narrative:
Demand for cheese is steady in retail markets, while food service demand is, reportedly, increasing. Contacts say that educational institutions' purchasing of cheese is picking up as schools are starting to reconvene, following their winter breaks. International demand for cheese is unchanged. Port congestion and a shortage of truck drivers continue to cause delays to deliveries of loads. Severe weather in some parts of the West is causing further delays to loads of cheese and production supplies. Spot purchasers say that there is no change in availability of either cheese barrels or blocks. Milk availability is increasing in the region, though some cheese makers report that snow is slowing the delivery of supplies to production facilities. Cheese production is steady to lower as delays to production supplies and ongoing staffing shortages are preventing some plant managers from running full schedules.


WESTERN WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
In the West, wholesale prices are up $.0450 for process, and up $.0825 for cheddar block, cuts and Monterey Jack. Swiss cut wholesale prices are unchanged from the previous week.
secondary source info:
CME GROUP MONTHLY AVERAGES
The CME Group December 2021 monthly average price for barrels, $1.6548, is up from the November 2021 monthly average price of $1.5375, and up from the monthly average of a year ago, $1.4609. The December average price for blocks, $1.8930, is up from the November 2021 monthly average of $1.7408, and up from the monthly average of a year ago, $1.6249.

The average price for the year of 2021 was $1.5688 for barrels and $1.7140 for blocks.
